<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Company News (This Week): Germany due for a respite from
shocks - Metallgesellschaft/Siemens
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The worst should be over by Wednesday. By then, Metallgesellschaft's
shell-shocked shareholders and bankers should have delivered their verdict -
along with pledges to stump up DM3.2bn (Pounds 1.25bn) - on the new
management's rescue plan.
Provided there are no further unpleasant surprises from the metals, mining
and engineering group, things should start to improve on Thursday. That is
when Mr Heinrich von Pierer, chairman of Siemens - the epitome of German
corporate conservatism - will reflect on a sound year and perhaps offer some
tangible evidence of economic recovery.
Mr Kajo Neukirchen, the new Metallgesellschaft chairman, is also expected to
make an appearance before the press to throw more light on how he hopes to
take the group forward.
Although the financial rescue package is the work of Deutsche Bank and
Dresdner Bank, his role should not be under-estimated. One banker enthused:
'I'd love to see what the poor blighter can do when he gets to run a good
company.'
Mr von Pierer is in that fortunate position. At the Siemens press conference
he will review the group's 1.3 per cent earnings gain for last year. Given
the sea of red ink engulfing much of corporate Germany, it was as welcome as
the plan to invest DM2.4bn in a new plant in Dresden.
