<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Not taken in by vouchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Professor RICHARD ROSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Russians learned not to believe everything they saw on television long
before the launch of TV ads promising a fortune in return for a
privatisation voucher ('Yeltsin plans curbs on abuses of privatisation by
voucher', January 5). Our representative survey of Russians, supported by
the Foreign Office Know-How Fund, found the great majority of Russians have
a realistic idea of a voucher's worth, estimating its value at Rbs9,000
roubles (about Pounds 5). Moreover, 82 per cent reckon their voucher will
decline in value.
We can extend to Russia the aphorism of a pioneering student of public
opinion: 'Ordinary people are not fools'.
Richard Rose,
Centre for the Study of Public Policy,
University of Strathclyde,
Livingstone Tower,
26 Richmond Street,
Glasgow G1 1XH
</TEXT>
