<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television has long tended to be embarrassed by true experts (too hoity
toity, too serious) and instead has chosen for its presenters
'personalities' with a bit of knowledge and a lot of enthusiasm. In the arts
we have recently had the nun who spent her previous life in a caravan, and
now here comes stand-up comedian Billy Connolly to show us The Bigger
Picture. In the first of a six-part series on Scottish art, Connolly goes to
Rome to explain about the Grand Tour. Well, programme makers are as keen on
an expenses-paid trip to Italy as you or I would be (7.30 BBC2).
Perhaps we have previously had drama and documentary series on the same
subject transmitted simultaneously, but I cannot recall them. Last night
BBC2 screened its documentary series 'Auction', and tonight ITV begins its
drama Under The Hammer. Richard Wilson plays the motorcycle-riding
international art expert at 'Klinsky's', the auction house invented by John
Mortimer (9.00).
Cutting Edge (9.00 C4) looks into feuds between neighbours, over dogs,
noise, almost anything.
</TEXT>
