<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Neo-Tesco look services motorways
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turn left after the Burger King, pass the amusement arcade and you will
reach the Country Kitchen restaurant, complete with patisserie, salad bar,
and hot servery.
Not your local high street, but Granada's Chieveley service station near
Newbury, Berkshire, built in 1987 on a 50-mile stretch of the M4 between the
Heston and Membury service stations that had no toilets, food or fuel.
All the signs are that it will be the model for the new service stations
promised last week. Granada - which with Forte's Welcome Break dominates the
53-station market with a score each - sees de-regulation as an opportunity
to establish a brand identity, not to revolutionise the service-station
concept.
Mr Ian Dunstall, the commercial director of Granada Hospitality, said:
'Historically there has been no branding between operators, with people
defining a station by location rather than operator.'
The most sensitive motorists will be disappointed to hear that the
prevailing 'neo-Tesco' style of station is unlikely to be overtaken by
anything more elegant this decade. Granada plans to standardise its stations
over the next few years so that visitors will hardly tell the difference
between stops on the M25 and one on the M1.
It will build three stations in the next three years, costing some Pounds
20m each. Meanwhile, it is installing a Burger King on every site and
spending Pounds 10m on converting the interiors of its oldest developments.
'Criticism tends to be directed at the ambience internally,' Mr Dunstall
said. 'People will be able to find their way round as easily as their local
Sainsbury's'
Forte points out that the government has protected against an explosion of
fast-food outlets along motorways by insisting that operators continue to
provide 24-hour access, fuel, free parking and toilets.
Mr Richard Power, head of corporate communications at Forte, said: 'The
experienced operators will open a number of new outlets, but they are likely
to be smaller than those built under the old system.'
He predicts an increase in the provision of facilities so that outlets will
be 'as much a place to relax as to eat'. Beyond that, Forte says its new
Welcome Break developments will not be much different from existing ones.
Smaller, more frequent service stations thus appear to be the way forward.
But greater competition seems unlikely to attract significant new entrants.
Accor, the French leisure group, recently showed some interest in a site on
the M25. It has withdrawn, however, worried that the prime sites had already
been snapped up. It was also put off by the requirement to provide fuel as
well as catering facilities on site.
The 24 new service stations - four with planning permission - which are now
in the pipeline are the product of de-regulation. Until now, stations had to
be spaced at least 30 miles apart.
The government has given the private sector responsibility for picking
sites, acquiring the land and seeking planning permission. Some are worried
about the still-unwieldy nature of the planning process. Mr Peter Dixon, of
consultants Grimley JR Eve's motorway and roadside development team, said:
'Motorway service area de-regulation was announced 16 months ago. It's a bit
rich to boast that four have obtained planning permission after so long.'
</TEXT>
