<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Tecs under fire for 'basic deficiencies'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Training and Enterprise Councils, set up by the government to spearhead
training improvements and stimulate local economies, will drift into a
secondary role unless reforms are made, says a study led by Professor Robert
Bennett of the London School of Economics, published today.
It is the first significant independent examination of the 82 employer-led
Tecs and their Scottish equivalents, Local Enterprise Companies.
Tecs, and to a lesser extent Lecs, are criticised on a number of fronts
including widely differing financial management.
The National Audit Office is looking at the effectiveness of the Department
of Employment's action to improve Tecs' financial control systems.
Tecs are also criticised in the LSE report for a lack of skilled staff. Many
staff are civil servants on secondment and the study recommends an immediate
end to this practice, which is not due to finish until 1996.
It also identifies 'fundamental deficiencies in the structure of Tecs'. The
study says the government has given the councils an unclear job. The
original mission for Tecs was to foster local economic growth and strengthen
the UK's skills base.
Yet most of the government's finance for Tecs is earmarked for training the
unemployed. Tecs play only a small part in local economic development, and
have few opportunities to become more involved.
Others recommendations made by Prof Bennett, including the suggestion that
Tecs could merge with chambers of commerce, are likely to be controversial.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, and Mr David Hunt,
the employment secretary, are to decide shortly whether they will approve
such moves.
Several Tecs would like to merge with chambers while others are strongly
opposed.
The proposal that the new combined Tecs and chambers should be more
independent of the government, and that they should be able to receive a
levy from the non-domestic rate, is likely to be politically unacceptable.
Prof Bennett, who believes chambers of commerce have more legitimacy because
of their local business membership and the democratic election of their
councils, is an advocate of Continental-style chambers. These have
substantial regulatory relationships with local employers.
He said yesterday: 'The government has not given Tecs the means to achieve
the grand vision.'
Mr Edward Roberts, chairman of the Tec National Council, said: 'There are no
quick fixes. Tecs have been set up over the past three years. We need a
serious sustained effort over the next decade. Some of the issues raised by
the study are being dealt with.'
Local Empowerment and Business Services. Britain's Experiment with Tecs. UCL
Press, Gower Street, London WC1E 6BT. Pounds 45.
</TEXT>
