<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / ITV merger plans worry advertisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Advertisers have protested to fair trading and television regulators about
concentration of TV advertising sales that will take place after proposed
mergers in the industry.
The Office of Fair Trading last week extended its investigation into
Granada's Pounds 700m bid for London Weekend Television and is believed to
be looking at concerns expressed by the Incorporated Society of British
Advertisers.
The society has told the OFT and the Independent Television Commission that
sales houses may have too much power.
Laser, the LWT sales house, also sells for Yorkshire-Tyne Tees, in which
Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a stake. The Time Exchange, the
Granada sales house, is a joint venture with Scottish and also sells for
Grampian and Border.
The two sales houses have more than 40 per cent of the ITV advertising
market.
