<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Boundary changes may remove familiar faces from Commons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Several prominent MPs may find themselves defending marginal seats at the
next general election if proposals to redraw their constituency boundaries
are implemented this year.
Party managers say that four government members - Mr Nicholas Soames, the
food minister, Sir George Young, the housing minister, Sir John Wheeler,
Northern Ireland minister, and Sir Derek Spencer, the solicitor-general -
will find that, on the basis of votes at the last general election, boundary
changes should mean that their seats go to Labour.
The Boundary Commissions for England, Scotland and Wales, which are charged
with ensuring that constituency electorates remain roughly the same size,
are steadily reshaping Britain's general election map for the first time
since 1983.
Their proposals are not due to be completed until the end of the year. But
they have already forced at least four members of the government and about
20 other MPs to start considering their options if they wish to avoid losing
their seats at the next election. Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor
whose current seat is being abolished, is among prominent backbenchers in
the same position. Others include Mr David Alton, the Liberal Democrat MP,
and Dame Janet Fookes, Tory MP for Plymouth Drake and deputy speaker of the
House.
However, Labour and Conservative party managers warned at the weekend that
the changes may affect several other MPs who remain unaware that the
spotlight will fall on them.
An official at one of the major parties who is monitoring the changes said
that the successor to Mrs Edwina Currie could find that the changes turn her
Derbyshire South constituency into one of the most marginal Tory seats. Mrs
Currie, who will contest the Bedfordshire South seat in the European
Parliament this year, is to leave the Commons at the next general election.
At the last election Mrs Currie held her seat with a majority of 4,568 over
the Labour candidate. However, there are proposals to withdraw from her
constituency a ward which contributed about 2,000 of that majority. Party
managers believe that Sir George Young will find that his Ealing and Acton
constituency is strongly Labour-leaning at the next election, after five
Hammersmith wards have been added.
Officials from the Conservative and Labour parties say Sir John Wheeler will
have problems with his Westminster North constituency (due to become
Regent's Park and Kensington North), which he defended with a majority of
just 3,733 at the last election.
For Mr Soames, the loss of part of the Mid-Sussex District from Crawley
could dent the 7,765 majority which he had at the last election. Although he
is not affected by current proposals, Mr Winston Churchill will have to fend
off a Labour attempt to have his constituency abolished instead of Mr Gerald
Kaufman's. Both MPs have seats in the Greater Manchester area, where the
Boundary Commission has to select one constituency for abolition.
'In England only 17 out of the 46 counties have yet been decided upon by the
commission,' said an official at one of the major parties. 'There is still a
lot of water to go under the bridge.'
Constituency boundaries are being redrawn because demographic changes have
led to a sharp shift in populations out of metropolitan centres and into the
shire counties over the last decade. This has created expectations that the
restructuring of the political map will favour the Conservatives. According
to Westminster Communications, a political consultancy, the Tories would
have won six more seats at the 1992 election and Labour lost one had the
proposed changes been implemented at that time.
If their worst fears are realised, some of these MPs could have the
opportunity of fighting some of the 20 or so seats that will be created by
the Boundary Commission for England at the next election. However, an MP
would have to judge whether it would be politically acceptable to desert a
constituency simply because it had turned into a marginal.
