<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Figures indicate recovery in commercial property
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The scale of the recovery in the commercial property market was underlined
yesterday by figures showing total returns from property of 18.6 per cent in
1993. Capital values grew by an average of 10.2 per cent.
These estimates by Richard Ellis, a firm of chartered surveyors, reveal a
sharp improvement on the previous year when commercial property made
negative returns of 2.1 per cent.
Property's strong performance, which was particularly pronounced in the last
few months of the year, stems from a historically high income return
together with a significant fall in investment yields.
The office sector made the greatest improvement of any sector of the
property market, moving from a 1992 return of minus 5.4 per cent to just
under 20 per cent. Total returns for retail property improved from 0.2 per
cent in December 1992 to 17.6 per cent a year later. Industrial property
improved over the year from 2.3 per cent to 18 per cent.
Office values rose by nearly 11 per cent, compared with a fall of 15.4 per
cent in 1992. Retail values rose by 10 per cent, compared with a fall of 7
per cent. Industrial values improved by nearly 16 percentage points to 8.4
per cent.
</TEXT>
