<DATE>940110
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Scott inquiry teeters between dynamite and damp squib: Jimmy
Burns explains why allegations of conspiracy and cover-up remain unclear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nine months after the start of its public hearings, it is still not clear
whether the Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry will produce political dynamite or a
damp squib.
Tomorrow, as the inquiry resumes its public hearings after the Christmas
recess, the former home secretary Mr Kenneth Baker will face his grilling.
Later this week the former foreign secretary Lord Howe will be called. They
will be followed next Monday by Mr John Major, the prime minister. Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence
secretary, and former foreign minister Mr Tristan Garel-Jones are also due
to appear.
What is yet to be established is whether the Thatcher administration
deliberately engaged in an organised conspiracy to supply arms illegally to
Iraq. It is also unclear whether Mr Major's government tried to ensure a
cover-up for past mistakes by issuing public-interest immunity certificates
to prevent government documents being disclosed in the trial of three former
executives of Matrix-Churchill, the machine-tool manufacturer.
In the eyes of some observers, the inquiry is running out of steam.
One former senior aide to Baroness Thatcher said: 'The inquiry is too bogged
down in minutiae. The worst Scott might conclude is that she (Lady Thatcher)
was presiding over an incompetent government.'
Yet others closer to the present administration have not ruled out the
possibility that the inquiry could put further strains on Mr Major and his
government.
'I haven't heard many colleagues talking about Scott recently,' said one
Conservative MP close to the government. 'But there is some explosive
material here.'
The issues with the most explosive potential are the use made by ministers
of immunity certificates authorising the withholding of documents, and the
extent to which British companies, with the complicity of officials and
ministers, were engaged in arming President Saddam.
At the time of the Matrix-Churchill trial in November 1992 ministers said
that disclosure would be injurious to the public interest, endanger the
lives of informants and threaten the efficiency of government.
Mr Heseltine said that Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, had advised
him it was his duty as a minister to sign the immunity certificates. He
later told the Commons that 'what I knew, what I should have known, the
questions I should have asked' were matters that would be 'properly examined
by the Scott inquiry'.
The inquiry has now established that officials and ministers, other than
those who signed the immunity certificates, knew that Matrix-Churchill
executives were involved in intelligence activities.
It has also established that export licences for dual-use equipment were
approved even though the intelligence services knew that British
manufacturers were contributing to the enhancement of Iraq's military
capability.
Lord Justice Scott is thought now to be prepared to dispute the
attorney-general's advice to the government. He may also seek to discover
why the Matrix-Churchill trial took place, given the remarks by the former
trade minister, Mr Alan Clark, that it should not have.
But lawyers who have been following the inquiry closely believe the judge's
terms of reference are too narrow to establish the full truth of what went
on in the 1980s. Mr Christopher Muttukumaru, the secretary to the inquiry,
said: 'We are not a general investigating authority looking at the extent to
which companies breached export regulations. Our interest is in establishing
what the government knew about companies breaching export regulations.'
Further controversy could arise from the balance the judge seems to have
tried to maintain between the interests of justice and the interests of
Whitehall. 'The judge wants to be seen to be scrupulously fair so that his
report will be taken that much more seriously,' said one of his officials.
Some Whitehall officials believe ministers have tried to pass blame on to
them and warn they could kick up a fuss if they end up as scapegoats. 'We
feel as if we've been dumped on,' one witness grumbled.'
A high-ranking political source said this week that Whitehall was awaiting
with particular anticipation the evidence of Sir Robin Butler, cabinet
secretary and head of the civil service, whose guidance notes put the onus
of political responsibility on ministers.
But the inquiry is taking much longer than expected. The publication of the
judge's final report is not expected until the end of the summer and until
the furore that surrounded its instigation has dissipated.
It may now be all the harder to detect whether the inquiry will focus more
on political responsibility, or opt instead for a broad critique of the
inefficiencies of government and the shortcomings of legislation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
