<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Inquiry stokes Italian political fires
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's fragile eight-month government headed by Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi
faces one of its sternest tests this week as parliament votes on a
no-confidence motion on Wednesday which could determine Mr Ciampi's future
and the timing of new elections.
The political tension rose over the weekend after magistrates started
interrogating Mr Maurizio Broccoletti and Mr Luigi Bisignani, two central
figures in the long-running political corruption scandal, who returned to
Italy last week. Both are believed to have access to important evidence
which could affect the future of the present government and influence this
week's parliamentary debate.
The most explosive testimony is expected to come from Mr Broccoletti, a top
secret service administrator, extradited from Monaco on Thursday. He has
claimed a string of senior ministers regularly received payments from the
secret services over the past decade. Mr Broccoletti's allegations include
two previous interior ministers, administratively responsible for the secret
services, and the present incumbent, Mr Nicolo Mancino.
His claims, which come as Italy's political parties manoeuvre frantically
for advantage ahead of the no-confidence vote, could provoke further
ministerial resignations. They also involve Mr Vincenzo Parisi, head of the
national police force. His offer to resign at the weekend was rejected by
the government, and he is expected to make a statement to magistrates this
week.
Allegations of high-level corruption by Mr Broccoletti before he went into
hiding rocked the political establishment last November and triggered an
unprecedented television address to the nation from President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro. Mr Broccoletti has now raised the stakes by accusing several
ministers, and Mr Scalfaro, a former interior minister, of covering up the
evidence.
The claims, however, have been treated with caution amid a stream of
conflicting allegations, including suggestions that some secret service
members have been conducting a disinformation campaign against the
government.
Mr Bisignani, one of the six remaining suspects in hiding in the corruption
scandal, surrendered to Milan police on Friday. Magistrates believe he
played a vital role passing illegal payments from industry to senior
politicians.
A former Rome correspondent for the Ansa news agency, Mr Bisignani had
high-level political contacts, notably in the Christian Democrat party. He
is also believed to have played a central role in transferring large
kickbacks from the Montedison chemicals group, where he was head of external
relations, to the parties during negotiations to dissolve the Enimont
chemicals joint venture in 1990.
</TEXT>
