<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Minority to fight Slovakia plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KOMARNO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
More than 3,000 elected officials from Slovakia's Hungarian minority agreed
at the weekend on a plan designed to protect and expand ethnic Hungarian
rights in Slovakia.
However, they pulled back from possible confrontation with the government by
dropping demands for an autonomous Hungarian province with its own
parliament.
There are about 600,000 ethnic Hungarians, representing 12 per cent of the
population, in Slovakia. They live mostly in provinces bordering Hungary in
a wide arc stretching from Bratislava, the Slovak capital in the west, to
Kosice and the Ukrainian border in the east.
Local representatives who met in a packed sports' hall in the southern
Slovak city of Komarno on Saturday, agreed to campaign for the establishment
of a single administrative district comprising either one or three regions
that would guarantee 'basic freedoms and human rights' for ethnic
Hungarians.
These proposals counter government plans included in a broader
administrative reform that would divide the areas inhabited by ethnic
Hungarians along north-south axes, thereby diluting Hungarian representation
at local and national level.
The meeting was called by an organisation established by mayors concerned at
what they perceive as growing discrimination against the Hungarian minority.
The removal of bilingual road signs earlier this year, and the passing of a
law forcing Hungarian women to add the Slovak 'ova' to their family name,
have caused widespread resentment.
</TEXT>
