<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Tory anger grows over handling of 'back to basics'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The back to basics initiative launched by Mr John Major appeared close to
foundering yesterday as questions mounted over the prime minister's handling
of the issue.
He defended the initiative vigorously, but there were signs of growing anger
among Tory MPs about the muddle over values which has dogged the campaign
since it was launched at the party conference in October.
In the past two weeks it was revealed that Mr Tim Yeo, the former
environment minister, had fathered two children out of wedlock by different
women; that Mr Alan Duncan, a minister's parliamentary assistant, had
resigned after disclosures about a business deal; and that a Conservative
backbencher was reported by his wife to have allegedly left her for a man.
It also emerged that Mr Steven Norris, transport minister, may face a
re-selection battle in his Epping constituency over claims that he has had
five mistresses.
Interviewed on the BBC's Breakfast with Frost, Mr Major sought to defuse the
row by denying that back to basics was a moral crusade, and drawing a
distinction between bad behaviour and tolerance of indiscretions. He said it
was 'proper' that ministers should resign if they behaved 'badly'. But 'if
someone commits a silly indiscretion, I am not in the business of a
witch-hunt'.
Mr Major urged his colleagues to show 'tolerance and understanding' to MPs
who behaved 'foolishly', and insisted that recent events did not invalidate
the initiative.
Senior Conservatives refused to comment publicly on the initiative in an
attempt to avoid stir-ring up fresh controversy when parliament resumes
tomorrow.
However, many rightwing MPs have been angered by the prime minister's
handling of the issue, which some see as a betrayal of family values. By
contrast, mainstream Conservatives who were worried by the moralistic tone
of the initiative are concerned that Mr Major has given a further hostage to
fortune by attempting to distinguish between classes of bad behaviour.
Sir Edward Heath, a strong supporter of the prime minister, said it was
'highly dangerous' for ministers to moralise. 'People, particularly the
British, dislike being preached at,' he said.
The confusion prompted a scathing attack by Mr John Smith, the Labour
leader, who claimed the initiative had 'collapsed in its own
contradictions'. Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, accused Mr
Major of offering the electorate 'bland slogans, muddled thinking and
complacency'.
Observer, Page 15
Lord Caithness resigns from government after death of his wife, Page 6
</TEXT>
