<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JAN 94 / Video game makers in US to set up age rating system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Video game manufacturers in the US, under political pressure to limit the
violence and sexual content of their products, have agreed to set up a
system to rate games according to their suitability for children.
In an initial proposal outlined this weekend at the Consumer Electronics
Show in Las Vegas, the Software Publishers Association, representing 1,100
companies, suggested a four-level system ranging from E for everyone to AO
for adults only.
Game makers would rate their own products, but they could be fined by an
industry-appointed council if they violated agreed guidelines. Some video
game companies, including Sega, which has overtaken Nintendo as US market
leader, already publish ratings with their games, but the industry is still
some way from final agreement on how to make the system general.
In the UK, makers, including 3DO, Atari, Electronic Arts and software
publishing houses, said they are developing a governing board to set
standards. At the moment there is no separate UK ratings system for games.
But as games get bloodier and more realistic with advanced graphics, the
Dollars 6bn (Pounds 4bn)-a-year industry is under mounting pressure from US
Congress and from customers to crack down on some of the more explicit
games.
Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and Senator Herb Kohl of Wisconsin
have proposed a bill that would impose ratings on the video game industry if
it fails to develop a satisfactory system of its own within a year.
Although the Software Publishers Association proposal is now expected to
form the basis for an industry-wide rating system, there is still
disagreement among game makers over how such a system should operate.
Some big companies favour an independent rating authority as the only way of
ensuring uniform and credible standards, while others argue that the cost
and delay involved in such an authority would be devastating to their
profitability.
Market grows by 15%, Page 6
</TEXT>
