<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / Finance and the Family: Slump in bonus payouts shows signs
of easing - The outlook for with-profits endowments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Anyone hoping to pay off a mortgage with an endowment policy in 1994 will be
watching closely the life insurance companies' announcements of this year's
bonus rates.
Bonuses on with-profits endowments have been cut quite savagely in the past
few years as insurance companies realised they could no longer afford to tap
into their reserves to pay for past miscalculations. This year, the cuts are
more modest and there are actually some increases.
The picture emerging from the handful of companies which announced their
bonus rates this week (more are due within the next few weeks) is that
anyone with a 10-year endowment maturing this year is looking at a lower
payout than in previous years, while some holders of 25-year policies will
face only marginal cuts or possible slight increases.
Actual bonus rates have been held to the same level as last year in some
cases, but the final payouts are lower because policies maturing this year
have accumulated fewer of the high bonuses of the 1980s.
The final payout on a with-profits endowment policy is made up of the sum
assured and all bonuses. Reversionary bonuses, added annually, cannot be
taken away once they have been given. Sometimes, reversionary bonuses are
calculated in two parts: an ordinary bonus, which is a percentage of the sum
assured; and a bonus on previous bonuses, so that growth is compounded.
These build up over the life of a policy.
Finally, a terminal bonus is added to the policy when it matures, to pass on
a share of any investment returns not already allocated with annual bonuses.
Terminal bonuses can be more than 100 per cent of the sum assured.
With-profits endowment policies are, however, designed to smooth out
investment returns over time. In a year when shares do well (most life funds
are invested mainly in equities, along with some property and fixed interest
securities), bonuses will usually be less than the stock market growth rate
so that, in years when stocks do not do so well, a similar bonus can still
be paid.
Actuaries have to guess what average investment returns will be over the
life of the policy. If they get it wrong, and pay far too much for several
years when actual returns are low, they will eventually have to compensate
by paying too little when investment returns are better. This is what has
been happening recently.
In 1990, bonuses were raised when they should have been cut. Bonus cuts and
slightly better investment returns in subsequent years may not yet have
quite compensated for the dent that made in reserves.
Cuts have slowed this year but the picture is not entirely rosy: most
insurance companies say bonuses are likely to fall further in future, as
high rates can no longer be justified in times of low inflation and expected
lower investment returns. Larger cuts were prevented this year only because
of spectacular stock market performance towards the end of 1993.
Bonuses on unitised with-profit endowments have also been cut by most
companies this year, but they depend less on the discretion of the actuaries
and more on the actual performance of the investment fund.
Some insurers have to be particularly cautious with 10-year payouts this
year because there are larger than usual volumes of 10-year policies
maturing. Life assurance premium relief was abolished in 1984 and many
people rushed to buy policies before the deadline. Miscalculations this year
could cost insurers more than normal.
Although returns from endowments are falling, insurance companies are keen
to stress that, for a relatively low-risk investment, they still provide a
respectable return above inflation, which has also been falling.
For example, a Norwich Union with-profits endowment taken out 25 years ago
by a 29-year-old man paying Pounds 30 a month would now be worth Pounds
58,694, representing an annual yield of 12.9 per cent. A 10-year policy on
the same basis is now worth Pounds 6,674, a yield of 11.9 per cent.
In comparison, Pounds 30 a month paid into a unit trust savings plan for the
median UK equity income fund, starting 10 years ago, would now be worth
Pounds 7,048, and Pounds 101,228 after 25 years (according to the
Association of Unit Trusts and Investment Funds, and Micropal). If the money
had been invested via a personal equity plan, those figures would be Pounds
7,724 and Pounds 146,993.
Of course, unit trusts do not provide any life insurance cover but many
endowments, particularly 10-year policies, are taken out purely as
investments with the life insurance element being a side issue.
Worries in recent times that some low-cost endowments would fail to pay off
the mortgages they were intended to cover appear to have faded somewhat for
policies maturing in this and the next few years. But if investment returns
are low throughout the 1990s, that might present a potential problem to
holders of policies from the late 1980s.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
