<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / Ladbroke shares rise as Stein decides to resign early
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Cyril Stein is bowing out early from Ladbroke Group, the hotels and
leisure company he built from a small bookmaker into a member of the FT-SE
100.
Mr Stein, 66 next month, announced in September that he would step down as
chairman at the end of 1993 after 37 years at the head of Ladbroke.
He planned to stay as a non-executive director for a further three years and
to head the property division, but yesterday Ladbroke said he had decided to
resign.
The company's shares put on 14p on the news, closing at 194p, on the
expectation that Mr Stein's departure would allow new management to impose
its own style on the group. The City had feared that a formidable
personality such as Mr Stein would find it impossible to take a back seat.
But there was sadness that, as one analyst said, 'the departure of a
chairman who has done great things for the company should be greeted by a
rally'.
Mr John Jackson, who took over as chairman on January 1, said Mr Stein had
liked the idea of staying on for another three years to complete 40 years
with Ladbroke. But as December 31 approached, it became increasingly clear
that it would be better both for himself and the group if he made a clean
break.
Mr Stein, who is to receive a Pounds 200,000 payment from the company, will
remain as a consultant to Ladbroke. 'He has a massive knowledge of racing
and a very large network of contacts,' said Mr Jackson.
Analysts believe Mr Stein's departure clears the way for property disposals
and a dividend cut.
During his tenure, Ladbroke never cut its dividend.
Ladbroke shares have suffered recently because of confusion over its
dividend policy.
Early last month the company cancelled its alternative scrip dividend after
its shares fell on an announcement that it would be taking advantage of the
new foreign income dividend scheme.
FIDs are perceived to be detrimental to pension fund investors, which
benefit from tax credits on normal dividends but not on foreign income
payouts.
London shares, Page 15
See Lex
</TEXT>
