<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Stein steps down
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is difficult not to feel a twinge of sympathy for Mr Cyril Stein after
Ladbroke's shares rose 7 per cent on news he is not even to be a
non-executive director any more. After all, Mr Stein has spent the best part
of 40 years at the helm. The market's ingratitude has a certain logic just
the same. It was always difficult to imagine Mr Stein taking a back seat at
board meetings. His departure will strengthen Ladbroke's resolve to get out
of property and, presumably, to cut the dividend to a sustainable level.
Above all it signals that the new management, which promises to be more
open, is very much in charge.
A flow of other announcements - the appointment of a couple of strong
non-executive directors, for example, and some new faces to reinforce the
management of the betting and hotels divisions - should help maintain the
share price recovery. The new team still faces some difficult calls,
however, not least over the speed with which it sells out of property when
prices are rising and disposals could prove dilutive. Assuming no skeletons
fall out of the cupboard when the door is opened, the task should not
require further significant write-downs. Though some adjustment to hotel
values may be needed, gearing should not be a particular problem.
The dividend must still be cut simply to restore cover rather than in a bid
to conserve cash. Texas Homecare will remain difficult for some time. But
Ladbroke's other two legs will be a strongly-branded hotel operation
balanced by a cash-rich betting business which may offer opportunities for
international expansion. That is not necessarily a recipe for spectacular
growth once cyclical recovery is out of the way, but Ladbroke's attraction
would increase relative to Forte, which has had to sell some cash-generative
businesses to repair its balance sheet.
</TEXT>
