<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Bourses stage turnround after
early gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday morning was gloomy, as Mr Albert Edwards, the Kleinwort Benson
strategist, reduced his weighting for Europe excluding the UK by a swingeing
seven percentage points, from 15 to 8 per cent.
However, bourses staged a turnround in the afternoon following the fall in
US December unemployment figures, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT moved from a fall of 8.58 to 2,211.64 on the session, down 2.4 per
cent on the week, to 2,224.95 at the end of the post-bourse. Mr Nigel
Longley of Commerzbank said that there was a lot of short covering after the
US unemployment figures.
Turnover rose from DM8.2bn to DM10.8bn. Metallgesellschaft was requoted,
falling DM52.50 to DM218 on the session and recovered a token DM4 of that in
the afternoon. Deutsche Bank, with apparently the greatest banking exposure
to the debacle, recovered DM4 to DM863 on the session, and another DM7.50 to
DM870.50 after hours.
Commerzbank announced a deep discount rights issue and a rise in dividend
which put it on a high, 4 1/2 per cent yield to German shareholders. It rose
DM2.80 on the session to DM382.50, and soared to DM391 later. Mr Peter
Thorne, banking analyst with Paribas Capital Markets in London, was
cautious: 'Commerzbank was under-provided for LDC risks a couple of years
ago,' he said, 'and there must be a suspicion in the market that it is
lagging behind in provisions for bad and doubtful debts in the corporate
sector.'
PARIS posted a strong afternoon rebound which left the CAC 40 index 32.4
higher at 2,307.55, up 1.7 per cent on the week in heavy turnover of
FFr7.4bn.
Automotive stocks, higher in mid-week on hopes of government support for the
industry, led the gains with Peugeot up FFr42, or 5.4 per cent at FFr817 and
Michelin FFr11.80, or 5.5 better at FFr226.10.
Metaleurop fell FFr6 to FFr77.40 after FFr73.30, and being suspended
limit-down at one point; Eurotunnel eased FFr2.25 to FFr56.25 on profit
 taking after weeks of steady gains.
ZURICH closed at its fifth consecutive record high with firmer US bond and
equity markets providing late support. The SMI index added 21.0 to 3,042.9
for a rise this week of 2.9 per cent.
Nestle, SFr28 higher at SFr1,343, topped the active list, and other leaders
included UBS, up SFr17 at SFr1,399, and Roche certificates, SFr105 higher at
SFr6,490.
Further demand for cyclicals took Georg Fischer bearers SFr75 higher to
SFr1,300 and BBC Brown Boveri firmed SFr21 to SFr1,150. However, Sulzer
which rose strongly earlier this week, shed SFr10 to SFr900 on
profit-taking.
Shares in Holderbank fell SFr20 to SFr965 after the cement producer said it
planned to raise its stake in Holnam, the US subsidiary, to 100 per cent
from 95 per cent.
AMSTERDAM ended an active week in subdued mood but still managed to climb
off earlier lows to book a cumulative 2.5 per cent gain on the renamed AEX
over its first five sessions. The index added 0.45 to to close at 424.02,
having posted an early intraday high of 425.41.
KLM began firm before a sudden burst of British buying took the shares up 4
per cent in about 30 minutes amid speculation that a widely expected share
issue may be imminent. After a day's high of Fl 45.00 they edged back to
finish Fl 1.50 ahead at Fl 44.60.
MILAN succumbed to immediate political worries and next Wednesday's
parliamentary vote of confidence and the Comit index shed 14.6 or 2.4 per
cent to 596.90. The index has fallen by 3.6 per cent over the week.
Montedison dominated trading, as it has all week, dipping L9 to L885.90.
Heavy arbitrage with its rights issue accounted for volume of 40m shares.
Ferruzzi shed L252 or 15.5 per cent to L1,427 also amid arbitrage with its
rights. Monday is the last day for both cash calls.
BRUSSELS hit yet another high, the Bel-20 index ending 8.81 better at
1,498.22 for a gain of 1.7 per cent on the week, helped by an interest rate
cut late on Thursday by the Banque Nationale de Belgique.
STOCKHOLM found firm demand which took the Affarsvarlden general index 36.2
or 2.5 per cent higher at a record 1,475.0.
Hennes &amp; Mauritz, the retailer, closed SKr26 or nearly 10 per cent higher at
SKr298 amid expectations that a controversial advertising campaign could
have the same impact on sales as one two years ago that featured the model,
Cindy Crawford.
B shares in Gambro, the medical equipment company rose SKr14 to SKr395 on
expectations of strong growth in the price.
ATHENS ended 5.7 per cent higher on the day and 12.4 per cent better on the
week, the general index closing 58.44 higher at 1,077.83 on technical and
sentiment grounds.
Written and edited by William Cochrane and Michael Morgan
