<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the Markets): Gold
price fails to hold gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The gold market was left treading water this week after a buying surge
proved insufficient to buoy the metal's price to the Dollars
400-a-troy-ounce level.
Having begun the new year with a Dollars 3.50 jump, aided by a strong rise
in silver, the gold price added another Dollars 2.35 on Wednesday to reach a
five-month peak of Dollars 396.60 an ounce. But the two-day advance was
wiped out on Thursday as computer programmes used by some US institutional
investors sent out almost unanimous 'sell' signals.
The fall, which took the price to Dollars 385.25 an ounce at one point, was
seen by some analysts as representing merely a badly-needed pause for breath
before a fresh assault on the Dollars 400 barrier. However, Mr Ted Arnold,
analyst at the Merrill Lynch financial services group, warned that physical
demand for gold was 'dropping like a stone'.
The price recovered to close yesterday at Dollars 388.25 an ounce, down
Dollars 2.50 on the week, but dealers told the Reuter news agency that stiff
resistance was building in the Dollars 390s. 'What we are seeing now is the
difference between dealers' ambitions for the new year and what the market
can actually do,' said one.
The silver market, which had been pushed sharply higher on concern over the
risings in Mexico, also surrendered its gains, the cash price in London
ending at Dollars 5.05 1/2 an ounce, down six cents on the week.
News of big rises in London Metal Exchange warehouse stocks pushed copper
and zinc prices still lower yesterday, after both metals had already
sustained substantial falls earlier in the week.
Last week's end-year profit-taking in the copper market spilled over into
Tuesday's trading, when the three months price fell Dollars 36 to Dollars
1,752.25 a tonne. A Dollars 17 bounce on the following day had been wiped
out by yesterday's close.
Defying the downtrend was aluminium, which shrugged off news of another LME
stocks increase to rise Dollars 3 yesterday to Dollars 1,149.50 a tonne in
the three months position, up Dollars 24.25 on the week. Dealers explained
that buyers were being encouraged by hopes of progress at the next
multilateral meeting on stemming the Russian aluminium supply glut, which is
scheduled to be held in Brussels later this month.
A depressed week for cocoa prices ended with further losses yesterday in
response to rumours of an imminent devaluation of the CFA franc, the
currency of, among others, the Ivory Coast, the world's biggest cocoa
producer. At the London Commodity Exchange the May futures price dipped to
Pounds 893 a tonne at one stage, before ending the day at Pounds 906, down
Pounds 23 on the week and Dollars 40 below Tuesday's peak.
LCE coffee futures fared somewhat better, the March position closing
yesterday at Dollars 1,194 a tonne, down Pounds 5 on the day and Pounds 4 on
the week, after trading between Dollars 1,181 and Dollars 1,209.
Seasonal cheer came late to the oil market, which had ended 1993 near 5-year
lows. A change of sentiment this week saw the London International Petroleum
Exchange's March Brent blend futures position climb to a high of Dollars
14.51 a barrel before easing to Dollars 14.33 in late trading yesterday,
still up 93 cents the week.
Mr Nauman Barakat, a vice-president for energy futures with Merrill Lynch in
New York, told Reuter that market psychology had changed in the short-term
and speculators were 'buying dips rather than selling rallies'.
