<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / Viacom and Blockbuster strike Dollars 8.4bn merger deal:
Link-up raises cash offer for Paramount to Dollars 105 a share
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Viacom, the US cable television company, and Blockbuster Entertainment, the
world's largest video retailer, last night announced an Dollars 8.4bn
(Pounds 5.6bn) merger agreement, together with a sharp increase in the cash
being offered by Viacom in the five-month-old takeover battle for Paramount
Communications.
Viacom, with financial help from Blockbuster, increased its cash offer for
50.1 per cent of Paramount's stock from Dollars 85 a share to Dollars 105 a
share, or Dollars 6.5bn, topping the Dollars 92 a share cash offer on the
table from rival QVC Network.
However, Viacom also substantially reduced the value of the package of
securities it is offering Paramount shareholders for the remaining 49.9 per
cent of the company.
The Viacom-Blockbuster merger will create a new US entertainment giant in
its own right, while the higher cash offer for Paramount appears to give
back to Viacom the initiative it lost to QVC last month.
Analysts say Paramount is likely to be won by the bidder putting most cash
on the table. Mr Barry Diller, chairman of QVC, and other companies which
have backed his bid, must now decide whether to match or top Viacom's cash
component.
The Viacom-Blockbuster deal takes the form of an all-paper offer by Viacom,
which will give Blockbuster investors 0.08 of a share of Viacom class A
voting stock, 0.60615 of a share of non-voting B stock, and one 'variable
common right' (a security whose value depends on the share price of Viacom)
for each Blockbuster share.
The deal values Blockbuster at about Dollars 8.4bn, based on the company's
closing share price on Thursday of Dollars 29 7/8 .
Blockbuster, which last September agreed to invest Dollars 600m in Viacom to
finance its Paramount bid, has now given additional assistance by agreeing
to invest Dollars 1.25bn in Viacom, provided it wins the Paramount battle,
through the purchase of 23m shares of Viacom B stock at Dollars 55 a share.
That compares to a closing price last night of Dollars 41, down Dollars 1
3/4 .
The shares being bought by Blockbuster at an above-market price give Viacom
the money to raise the cash element of its bid, while reducing by a similar
amount the number of shares being offered to Paramount shareholders for 49.9
per cent of their stock.
Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman of Viacom, will be chairman of the combined
Viacom-Blockbuster group and will own 61 per cent of voting stock. Mr Wayne
Huizenga, chairman of Blockbuster, will be vice-chairman.
The board of the new company will have six directors nominated by Viacom,
three from Blockbuster and two from Nynex, the Baby Bell telephone company
which is also financially backing the Paramount bid. However, no new funds
were provided yesterday by Nynex.
Viacom is best known for its innovative cable television networks, such as
the pop music channel MTV, while Blockbuster has been expanding beyond its
video retailing roots into music retailing, the Hollywood film industry and
theme parks.
US stocks Page 21
</TEXT>
