<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 94 / European markets up as rate fears ease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND and MICHAEL MORGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock markets in Europe advanced yesterday after significantly improved
employment statistics from the US eased fears of upward pressures on global
interest rates.
In London, renewed buying of UK stocks from across the Atlantic drove the
FT-SE 100 index ahead by 43 points to 3,446, and the FT-SE Mid 250, covering
a broader range of shares, rose 63.5 to an all-time high of 3,912.5.
As in the hectic trading during the run-up to Christmas, it was US buying of
London stock index futures which ignited the share market. However, prices
were often forced higher yesterday because the unwillingness of investors to
sell shares has left marketmakers very short of stock.
British government bonds were also sharply higher, gaining more than 3/4 of
a point as interest rate fears subsided.
However, south-east Asian markets tumbled for a second day as Kleinwort
Benson, the British securities house, added its voice to those downgrading
their view of Pacific Rim markets.
Earlier in the week, Japan's Nomura cut its weightings on Hong Kong, Kuala
Lumpur and Manila, preferring Tokyo instead. Morgan Stanley took the view
that equity markets had reached unsustainably optimistic levels and
recommended a shift from shares to cash.
Bangkok saw yesterday's biggest fall, plunging 5.5 per cent, while Kuala
Lumpur fell 4.6 per cent. Manila fell 4.1 per cent and Taiwan 3.9 per cent.
Hong Kong declined another 3.3 per cent in record turnover.
London shares, Page 15; World stocks, Page 21; Lex, Page 26; Markets,
Weekend, Page II
